## Prompt caching for direct API integrations

If your project calls the Anthropic API directly (Python `anthropic` SDK or TypeScript `@anthropic-ai/sdk`), you can reduce token costs by up to 90% on repeated static content using prompt caching.

**How it works**: add `cache_control: {"type": "ephemeral"}` to any content block you want cached. The cache lives for 5 minutes after the last write. Re-use the same content within that window → pay ~10% of normal input token rates.

**When to cache**: content that is static (>1024 tokens), reused across turns within the same session, and does not change between requests — e.g., a long system prompt, a static knowledge document, or a loaded spec file.

**When NOT to cache**: per-turn user messages, session state that changes each request, or any content under ~1024 tokens (the minimum cacheable block size).

**Model requirement**: prompt caching requires a latest Sonnet or Opus model. Check the [Anthropic model documentation](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/about-claude/models) for the definitive list of supported models at time of deployment.

### Python example

```python
import os
import anthropic

client = anthropic.Anthropic()

# TODO: set ANTHROPIC_MODEL env var to a current Sonnet or Opus model ID.
# See https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/about-claude/models for the
# authoritative list of caching-capable models.
model_id = os.environ["ANTHROPIC_MODEL"]

# System prompt is static — cache it
system_content = [
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "<your long static system prompt here>",
        "cache_control": {"type": "ephemeral"},  # cache this block
    }
]

response = client.messages.create(
    model=model_id,
    max_tokens=1024,
    system=system_content,
    messages=[
        {"role": "user", "content": "Hello!"}  # per-turn — not cached
    ],
)

# Monitor cache efficiency
usage = response.usage
print(f"Cache write tokens: {usage.cache_creation_input_tokens}")
print(f"Cache read tokens:  {usage.cache_read_input_tokens}")
print(f"Uncached tokens:    {usage.input_tokens}")
```

### TypeScript example

```typescript
import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";

const client = new Anthropic();

// TODO: set ANTHROPIC_MODEL env var to a current Sonnet or Opus model ID.
// See https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/about-claude/models for the
// authoritative list of caching-capable models.
const modelId = process.env.ANTHROPIC_MODEL!;

// System prompt is static — cache it
const systemContent = [
  {
    type: "text" as const,
    text: "<your long static system prompt here>",
    cache_control: { type: "ephemeral" as const }, // cache this block
  },
];

const response = await client.messages.create({
  model: modelId,
  max_tokens: 1024,
  system: systemContent,
  messages: [
    { role: "user", content: "Hello!" }, // per-turn — not cached
  ],
});

// Monitor cache efficiency
const { usage } = response;
console.log(`Cache write tokens: ${usage.cache_creation_input_tokens}`);
console.log(`Cache read tokens:  ${usage.cache_read_input_tokens}`);
console.log(`Uncached tokens:    ${usage.input_tokens}`);
```

See [docs/process-kit/prompt-caching-consumer-guide.md](docs/process-kit/prompt-caching-consumer-guide.md) for the full "when to cache" heuristic, multi-turn patterns, and monitoring guidance.
